<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911024-0072</DOCNO><DOCID>911024-0072.</DOCID><HL>   Continental Corp. Cost Cuts</HL><DATE>10/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17</SO><CO>   CIC LABOR</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>PROPERTY andamp; CASUALTY INSURANCE (INP)INSURANCE (INS)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Continental Corp. said it plans to offer anearly retirement program for about 400 veteran employees, ata cost of about $10 million to be reflected in the fourthquarter.   Employees with a combination of age and years of servicetotaling at least 85 in 1992 will be eligible for theprogram, to be effective in January. The insurance companysaid it expects about half the eligible 400 to accept theoffer. The company currently has about 14,000 employees.</LP><TEXT>   Continental is also introducing other cost-cuttingmeasures, including deferrals on annual salary raises,delayed hiring and restrictions on the use of officetemporary help.   Company officials were not available to clarify how muchthe company expects to save with the early-retirement programand other measures.</TEXT></DOC>